            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000418": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000418",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000419": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000419",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000389\"><span class=\"label\">[33]</span></$link> <i>Yashiki</i>, or spread-out house, was the name given to the palace and grounds of a daimiō's city residence, and also to the barracks occupied by his retainers, both in city and country. In the city the barracks of the samurai were built as a hollow square, in the centre of which stood the palace and grounds of their lord, and this whole place was the daimiō's <i>yashiki</i>. In the castle towns the daimiō's palace and gardens stood within the castle inclosure, surrounded by a moat, while the <i>yashikis</i> of the samurai were placed without the moat. They in turn were separated from the business part of the village sometimes by a second or third moat. By life in castle and <i>yashiki</i> we mean the life of the daimiō, whether in city or country.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000420": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000420",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000421": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000421",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000422": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000422",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\">\n</div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000423": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000423",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-9c6670 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-e3b0c4 twpub-6a4248ca8f6e64ca-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"footnotes\"><div class=\"footnote\"><p><a></a><$link class=\"pginternal\" to=\"$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000401\"><span class=\"label\">[34]</span></$link> The Japanese language is full of expressions showing different shades of meaning in the politeness or respect implied. There are words and expressions which superiors in rank use to inferiors, or <i>vice versa</i>, and others used among equals. Some phrases belong especially to the language of the high-born, just as there are common expressions of the people. Some verbs in this extremely complex language must be altered in their termination according to the degree of honor in which the subject of the action is held in the speaker's mind.</p></div></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000424": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/6a4248ca8f6e64ca/text/000000424",
